aine. Under EU rules, they have until March 28 to cancel contracts, but hav=
e no way of repossessing the aircraft after Russia moved to keep them withi=
n its borders.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so Russia,=
=C2=A0or rather Russian airlines,=C2=A0<em>have </em>essentially=C2=A0defau=
lted on those leases: The lessors have asked for the planes back, Russia ha=
s refused, and the lessors are not getting lease payments due to sanctions.=
 And Russia=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>want to negotiate some sort of restruct=
uring of these leases, so that (1) it can keep flying the planes and (2) it=
 can retain enough goodwill in the capital markets to one day lease more pl=
anes again. But it can=E2=80=99t, for the reasons we talked about before: T=
he lessors are=C2=A0<em>not allowed to sit down to negotiate with Russia</e=
m>, because of the sanctions. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
